The article discusses the importance of affordable, high-speed internet access for every person in America, regardless of their location or income. It states that when President Joe Biden and the author took office, 30 million people in the country did not have access to high-speed internet, with certain communities being disproportionately affected. To address this issue, they worked with Democrats and Republicans in Congress to invest $65 billion in affordable, high-speed internet, aiming to lower costs and connect every household in the nation. The article also mentions that the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) recently adopted rules to prevent digital discrimination in internet access based on income, race, ethnicity, religion, and national origin. These rules are seen as a way to protect civil rights, reduce costs, and increase internet access for Americans. The article concludes by emphasizing the importance of internet access in areas such as education, employment, healthcare, and global engagement, and the commitment of President Biden and the author to continue working towards making affordable, high-speed internet more accessible for everyone.